.SH NAME
psdraft \- add "draft" notices on PostScript language documents
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B psdraft
[ 
.BI -s string
] [
.BI -x xcoord
] [
.BI -y ycoord
] [
.BI -f font
] [
.BI -r angle
] [
.BI -g graylevel
] [
.BI -o
] [
.BI -p outfile
] [
.BI -P printer
] [
.I files
]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.I psdraft
reads in conforming \*(PS language files and inserts \*(PS language code to
print a 
string 
such as "DRAFT" in the margins, or anywhere on the page.
.sp
For example:
.RS
psdraft text.ps
.RE
produces a \*(PS file that, in addition to the image already described in
text.ps, prints the string "DRAFT" rotated 90 degrees in the right margin.
.RS
psdraft -s"Adobe Confidential" -r45 -x252 -y324 text.ps
.RE
produces a \*(PS file that includes the string "Adobe Confidential" in the
middle of the page, rotated 45 degrees.
.sp
The possible options are:
.TP
.BI -s string
puts
.I string
on the paper.  The default is "DRAFT".
.TP
.BI -r angle
rotates the string 
.I angle
degrees.  The default is 90.
.TP
.BI -x xcoord
puts the string at the 
.I xcoord
x-coordinate on the page.  The default is 575.
.TP
.BI -y ycoord
puts the string at the 
.I ycoord
y-coordinate on the page.  The default is 300.
.TP
.BI -g graylevel
specifies the gray level for printing the string.  The default is 0 (black).
.TP
.BI -f font
sets the font to be used for printing the string.  The default is
Times-Roman30. 
.sp
Font specifications have two parts:
a font name as known to the \*(PS printer (e.g., Times-Roman,
Times-BoldItalic, 
Helvetica, Courier), and a point size (1 point=1/72 inch; 8 point 
is a good small point size).  So Courier-Bold8 is 8 point Courier Bold, 
Helvetica12 is 12 point Helvetica.
.sp
.TP
.B -o
specify that the outline of the font should be used.  Default is not to use
outline. 
.TP
.BI -p out
causes the \*(PS file to be written to the named file rather than
being spooled for printing.  As a special case, 
.B -p-
will send the \*(PS language document to the standard output (which is the
default behavior).  
.TP
.BI -P printer
specifies that 
.I psdraft 
should get information about the dimensions of the
paper from the \*(PS Printer Description file for 
.I printer. 
This information is necessary to do rotation.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.IP PPDDIR
path for finding \*(PS Printer Description files.
.IP PSLIBDIR
path name of a directory to use instead of XPSLIBDIRX 
for then
.I psdraft 
prologue
